Hola Jose!

La primera pregunta de utilidad en la cadena!

The first useful question in the chain of comments.

I'm guessing that the answer may be in redundancy.

In any data stream, the noise is random, and the signal, if repetitious, is
not. Redundant signals add linearly. "True" noise adds as the root of the
sum of the squares. That gives about 3 dB of "gain" to the signal. Repeat
the redundant signal enough times and the signal "climbs" out of the noise.

Other comments welcome!

Bill
KT4YE

